{"dataset":"articles","provider":"pursuit","banner_url":"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0029/76781/The-older-Asian-Australians-boosting-health-literacy_26757a20-b6e0-4ec6-90c5-6f66ce1ddce4.jpg","id":"76774","text":"<div class=\"container\"><span><p>Older culturally and linguistically diverse (CALD) Australians were particularly vulnerable to COVID-19 and the <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1186/s12877-021-02352-1\" target=\"_self\">social and mental consequences</a> of lockdowns.</p><p>This was exacerbated by <a href=\"https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/full/10.1177/0022022120927461\" target=\"_self\">language barriers</a>, and an absence of culturally appropriate and accessible content. This has led older CALD Australian to become <a href=\"https://bmcpublichealth.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12889-022-13256-z\" target=\"_self\">disengaged with public health messages</a>.</p><p>And this group is growing.</p></span><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0029/76781/varieties/64w.jpg 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0029/76781/varieties/160w.jpg 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0029/76781/varieties/375w.jpg 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0029/76781/varieties/768w.jpg 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0029/76781/varieties/960w.jpg 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0029/76781/varieties/1280w.jpg 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0029/76781/varieties/1440w.jpg 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0029/76781/varieties/1920w.jpg 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0029/76781/The-older-Asian-Australians-boosting-health-literacy_26757a20-b6e0-4ec6-90c5-6f66ce1ddce4.jpg\" alt   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>Some 18 percent of Australians over 65 speak a language other than English at home. Photo: Getty Images </figcaption></figure></div><span><p>The <a href=\"https://www.aihw.gov.au/reports/older-people/older-australians/contents/demographic-profile#Age\" target=\"_self\">latest data</a> shows that one in five Australians over 65 were born in non-English speaking countries and 18 per cent spoke a language other than English at home. Six per cent do not speak English well or at all.</p><p>Developing a strategic approach to effectively communicate with older CALD Australians is urgently needed for both the ongoing management of COVID-19 but also to improve their overall health literacy.</p></span><!--[--><!--noindex--><article class=\"ps-cta container\" data-component=\"CallToAction\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__flex\" data-v-1d83364b><div data-v-1d83364b><img src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0035/76985/varieties/375w.jpg\" data-v-1d83364b></div></div><div class=\"ps-cta__info\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__top\" data-v-1d83364b><p class=\"ps-cta__channel ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-text-uppercase\" data-v-1d83364b>Politics &amp; Society</p></div><a class=\"ps-cta__link ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-lh-120 ps-cta__black\" href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/it-s-time-to-build-south-asia-literacy-in-australia?in_c=in_article_cta\" target=\"_self\" data-v-1d83364b><p data-v-1d83364b>It’s time to build South Asia literacy in Australia <i class=\"ps-icon--arrow-right ps-cta__black\" data-v-1d83364b></i></p></a></div></article><!--endnoindex--><!--]--><span><h2 class=\"center\">More than just proper translations</h2></span><span><p>Against the backdrop of the COVID-19 pandemic, our research team from the <a href=\"https://arts.unimelb.edu.au/school-of-culture-and-communication\" target=\"_self\">School of Culture and Communications</a> interviewed 31 older Asian migrants (aged 60 years and above) from the Chinese, Indonesian and Sri Lankan communities from November 2021 to January 2022.</p><p>The study period included one of Victoria’s lockdowns and its transition out of major COVID-19 restrictions.</p><p>Our participants faced English-language barriers when accessing official information and health advice about COVID-19. Timely and high-quality translations of vital health information were often lacking in both <a href=\"https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/nop2.1099\" target=\"_self\">health and aged care facilities</a> and everyday <a href=\"https://search.informit.org/doi/epdf/10.3316/informit.409752966362962\" target=\"_self\">community settings</a> throughout the pandemic.</p></span><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0030/76782/varieties/64w.jpg 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0030/76782/varieties/160w.jpg 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0030/76782/varieties/375w.jpg 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0030/76782/varieties/768w.jpg 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0030/76782/varieties/960w.jpg 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0030/76782/varieties/1280w.jpg 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0030/76782/varieties/1440w.jpg 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0030/76782/varieties/1920w.jpg 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0030/76782/The-older-Asian-Australians-boosting-health-literacy_b141af74-cdfe-4f98-ab2f-de5bae8a8a52.jpg\" alt   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>Older Asian Australians faced language and cultural barriers when accessing COVID-19 information. Photo: Getty Images </figcaption></figure></div><span><p>The problem, however, was more complicated as translation alone can’t tackle the issue.</p><p>As <a href=\"https://bmchealthservres.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12913-019-4859-6\" target=\"_self\">previous studies</a> suggest, translations often fail to build <a href=\"https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/07481187.2020.1815101?journalCode=udst20\" target=\"_self\">culturally accessible and relevant content</a> for older CALD Australians.</p><p>Some participants could understand English and had access to local English media and health authorities’ information in Australia. However, they continued to seek COVID-19 news and information in their own language and from their home country.</p></span><!--[--><!--noindex--><article class=\"ps-cta container\" data-component=\"CallToAction\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__flex\" data-v-1d83364b><div data-v-1d83364b><img src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0020/84008/varieties/375w.jpg\" data-v-1d83364b></div></div><div class=\"ps-cta__info\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__top\" data-v-1d83364b><p class=\"ps-cta__channel ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-text-uppercase\" data-v-1d83364b>Politics &amp; Society</p></div><a class=\"ps-cta__link ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-lh-120 ps-cta__black\" href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/australia-needs-to-embrace-asianness-as-part-of-australianness?in_c=in_article_cta\" target=\"_self\" data-v-1d83364b><p data-v-1d83364b>Australia needs to embrace ‘Asianness’ as part of ‘Australianness’ <i class=\"ps-icon--arrow-right ps-cta__black\" data-v-1d83364b></i></p></a></div></article><!--endnoindex--><!--]--><span><p>English language news and information in Australia could not sufficiently fulfill their information needs about COVID-19. In fact, we found that governments and health authorities often did not distribute vital health information via <a href=\"https://www.abc.net.au/news/2022-06-08/covid-public-health-information-victorian-government-study/101134738\" target=\"_self\">channels and platforms</a> that were easily accessible to our participants.</p><p>English and translated COVID-19 information was mainly distributed through mainstream (western or US-based) platforms like Facebook and Twitter.</p><p>However, none of our participants were active Twitter users and none of the Chinese participants (from both mainland China and Hong Kong) used Facebook.</p><p>Instead, they relied on a range of <a href=\"https://theconversation.com/ethnic-community-media-can-play-a-key-role-in-a-crisis-but-it-needs-our-support-195193\" target=\"_self\">ethnic language media and social media platforms</a> like WeChat, community WhatsApp groups and ethnic language YouTubers, inside and outside of Australia, to obtain COVID-19 related information.</p></span><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0031/76783/varieties/64w.jpg 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0031/76783/varieties/160w.jpg 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0031/76783/varieties/375w.jpg 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0031/76783/varieties/768w.jpg 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0031/76783/varieties/960w.jpg 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0031/76783/varieties/1280w.jpg 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0031/76783/varieties/1440w.jpg 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0031/76783/varieties/1920w.jpg 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0031/76783/The-older-Asian-Australians-boosting-health-literacy_82ea6c33-9424-4394-b883-cc185a9d7073.jpg\" alt   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>Flyers asking for submission for the Living through COVID-19 photo competition, in Indonesian, Simplified Chinese, and Sinhala. Picture: Supplied</figcaption></figure></div><span><h2 class=\"center\">Co-creation is the answer</h2></span><span><p>Like <a href=\"https://apo.org.au/sites/default/files/resource-files/2021-05/apo-nid312412.pdf\" target=\"_self\">many older Australians</a>, our participants have embraced digital technologies.</p><p>All but one used their smartphone regularly, and more than two thirds used more than one digital device every day.</p></span><!--[--><!--noindex--><article class=\"ps-cta container\" data-component=\"CallToAction\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__flex\" data-v-1d83364b><div data-v-1d83364b><img src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/80652/varieties/375w.jpg\" data-v-1d83364b></div></div><div class=\"ps-cta__info\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__top\" data-v-1d83364b><p class=\"ps-cta__channel ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-text-uppercase\" data-v-1d83364b>Health &amp; Medicine</p></div><a class=\"ps-cta__link ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-lh-120 ps-cta__black\" href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/indian-and-australian-health-workers-reach-out-on-covid-19?in_c=in_article_cta\" target=\"_self\" data-v-1d83364b><p data-v-1d83364b>Indian and Australian health workers reach out on COVID-19 <i class=\"ps-icon--arrow-right ps-cta__black\" data-v-1d83364b></i></p></a></div></article><!--endnoindex--><!--]--><span><p>Importantly, our participants wanted to use their digital skills to “do something” for their communities – organising community events on Zoom, creating a digital archive for community activities, sharing vital health information and news relevant to the community in social media groups, and combating fake news about COVID-19.</p><p>Our findings led us to a new project in the second half of 2022 to co-create digital COVIDSafe content with older Chinese, Indonesian and Sri Lankan migrants.</p><p>As part of the Victorian Government’s <a href=\"https://www.vic.gov.au/multicultural-communications-outreach-program\" target=\"_self\">Multicultural Communication Outreach Program</a>, we made <a href=\"https://cocreating-covidsafe.com.au/videos\" target=\"_self\">19 short videos</a> with older Asian Victorians to promote COVIDSafe behaviors.</p></span><div data-component=\"VideoBlock\" ><div class=\"container\" data-v-4bbde884><div class=\"row\" data-v-4bbde884><div class=\"col-12\" data-v-4bbde884><figure class=\"ps-figure ps-figure--full-width\" data-v-4bbde884><div class=\"ps-embed-video__wrapper\" data-v-4bbde884><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/d_OH25fbBug?autoplay=1&amp;rel=0\" id=\"vidlink\" class=\"ps-embed-video__link\" data-v-4bbde884><div class=\"ps-embed-video\" style=\"max-width:845px;max-height:480px;\" data-v-4bbde884><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAEAAAABCAQAAAC1HAwCAAAAC0lEQVR42mNkYAAAAAYAAjCB0C8AAAAASUVORK5CYII=\" alt style=\"background-image:url(https://i.ytimg.com/vi/d_OH25fbBug/maxresdefault.jpg?&amp;enablejsapi=1);max-width:845px;max-height:480px;\" data-v-4bbde884><div class=\"ps-embed-video__play-button\" data-v-4bbde884><svg id=\"playButtonSVG\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\"   viewBox=\"0 0 128 128\" fill=\"none\"><rect id=\"playButtonRect\"   rx=\"64\" fill=\"black\"></rect><path id=\"playButtonPath\" d=\"M42.666 100.934V26.2676L101.333 63.6009L42.666 100.934ZM50.666 86.4009L86.5327 63.6009L50.666 40.8009V86.4009Z\"></path></svg></div><div class=\"ps-embed-video__video-title\" style=\"display:none;\" data-v-4bbde884><span class=\"ps-embed-video__title\" data-v-4bbde884></span><span class=\"ps-embed-video__duration\" data-v-4bbde884></span></div></div><div class=\"ps-embed-video__iframe-wrapper\" style=\"display:none;\" data-v-4bbde884><iframe class=\"\" src   frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"autoplay\" allowfullscreen id=\"widget2\" title=\"Augmented Reality: Getting under the skin\" data-v-4bbde884></iframe></div></a></div><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-4bbde884>A video from the CoCreating COVIDsafe project featuring Sri Lankans busting COVID myths for their community. Video: Supplied</figcaption></figure></div></div></div></div><span><p>We also invited them to participate in a <a href=\"https://cocreating-covidsafe.com.au/photography-competition\" target=\"_self\">photo competition</a>, which resulted in a <a href=\"https://www.artsteps.com/view/63869e11056550e58abc2be3\" target=\"_self\">virtual gallery</a> and <a href=\"https://cocreating-covidsafe.com.au/exhibition\" target=\"_self\">physical exhibition</a>, that presents the participants’ emotions and memories of the pandemic, as well as showcasing their digital skills and creative talents.</p><p>Our aim was to use <a href=\"https://library.oapen.org/handle/20.500.12657/42574\" target=\"_self\">digital media as an enabler</a> for older Asian migrants’ voices and the community’s perspective of effective public health communication.</p></span><!--[--><!--noindex--><article class=\"ps-cta container\" data-component=\"CallToAction\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__flex\" data-v-1d83364b><div data-v-1d83364b><img src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0018/80613/varieties/375w.jpg\" data-v-1d83364b></div></div><div class=\"ps-cta__info\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__top\" data-v-1d83364b><p class=\"ps-cta__channel ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-text-uppercase\" data-v-1d83364b>Politics &amp; Society</p></div><a class=\"ps-cta__link ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-lh-120 ps-cta__black\" href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/finding-australia-s-new-asia-narrative?in_c=in_article_cta\" target=\"_self\" data-v-1d83364b><p data-v-1d83364b>Finding Australia’s new Asia narrative <i class=\"ps-icon--arrow-right ps-cta__black\" data-v-1d83364b></i></p></a></div></article><!--endnoindex--><!--]--><span><p>This led to diverse formats of health communications, from mimicking a soap-opera format (Sri Lankan) to creating ‘TikTok-like’ short videos (Chinese) to a documentary format about key religious and business figures’ experiences and advice (Indonesian).</p><p>The photo competition and virtual gallery was designed to build participants’ confidence in using digital media to ‘do things’ for their communities and acknowledge that their voices are indispensable in the public conversation about the ongoing management of COVID-19.</p><p>Digital co-creation should serve as a fundamental principle to developing effective and sustainable communication practices with older Australians.</p></span><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0036/76779/varieties/64w.jpg 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0036/76779/varieties/160w.jpg 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0036/76779/varieties/375w.jpg 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0036/76779/varieties/768w.jpg 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0036/76779/varieties/960w.jpg 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0036/76779/varieties/1280w.jpg 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0036/76779/varieties/1440w.jpg 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0036/76779/varieties/1920w.jpg 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0036/76779/The-older-Asian-Australians-boosting-health-literacy_2b193991-6783-48d2-bd24-d335a85b78ed.jpg\" alt   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>‘Memories and stories during COVID’, one of the category winners in the photography exhibition. Photo: Shirley Jeremic</figcaption></figure></div><span><p>With the right opportunities and encouragement, older Asian migrants will jump at the chance to participate in the creation and distribution of vital public health information. By co-creating, we can identify opportunities and areas require attention to support older CALD Australians’ health literacy.</p><p><span class=\"italics\">‘</span><a href=\"https://cocreating-covidsafe.com.au/exhibition\" target=\"_self\" class=\"italics\">Living through COVID-19: memories, beliefs and hopes’</a><span class=\"italics\"> photography exhibition is on at the Digital Studio, Arts West Building, University of Melbourne, Parkville from 20-31 March 2023.</span></p><p>Banner: Getty Images</p></span></div>\n<p>This article was first published on <a href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au\">Pursuit</a>. <a href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/the-older-asian-australians-boosting-health-literacy\">Read the original article.</a></p>","date_published":"2023-03-14T11:40:59+11:00","date_updated":"2023-03-14T11:40:59+11:00","url":"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/the-older-asian-australians-boosting-health-literacy","title":"The older Asian Australians boosting health literacy","summary":"COVID-19 exposed the shortcomings of Australia’s public health communication to older culturally and linguistically diverse communities","org_objects":[],"tag_objects":[],"author_objects":[{"name":"Dr Wilfred Wang","url":"https:\\/\\/pursuit.unimelb.edu.au\\/individuals\\/dr-wilfred-wang","orcid":"","fae_url":"https://findanexpert.unimelb.edu.au/profile/758878-wilfred-wang","email":""}],"citation_objects":[{"credentials":"Dr Wilfred Wang"}]}